title: iPad Pro 12.9" Mic Stand Holder

description.text:
After switching to the iPad Pro 12.9" from the iPad Air 2, I couldn't find a suitable and affordable tablet holder for the larger size. I already had one for the smaller ipads and decided to adapt its design to a larger one.
It's a geared design which allows to just place the tablet in the holder and by hand-tightening the bolts, it clamps the tablet to a tight fit.
On one of the long sides I added a holder/clamp for the Apple Pencil.

Printer:

CTC Bizer Dual

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

25% / 90%

Notes:

All brackets that need to resist some force as the studs, knobs and gears were printed at 90% infill. The others, like the actual tablet holders (in and out slides & center ring) were printed at 25% infill.
I used supports on all parts, because it was either needed or gave better results.

For the iPad Pro 12.9" you need to print:
1x Center-ring
1x Center Stud
1x Mic Stand Bracket
1x Knob
1x Knob Insert
2x Inner Side Bracket
2x Outer Side Slide
2x Inner Top Bracket
1x (or 2x) Outer Top Slide
1x (or 0x) Outer Bottom Pen Slide
4x Gear M5
4x Slider Knob

*) When you don't need the Apple Pencil holder you just use two Outer Top Slides.

Assembling

You'll need the following parts to complete assembly:

For attaching the 4 Inner Brackets to center ring:
12x Allen screw M3x12mm
12x Nut M3

For attaching the MIC Stand Bracket to the Center Stud:
1x M8x30mm hex bolt
1x M8 nut

For attaching Center Stud to Center Ring:
1x M8x30mm hex bolt
1x M8 lock-nut (allows for adjuistable tightening of the center ring without the risk of getting lose and adjust the force for turning the tablet from landscape to portrait)

For attaching the gears:
4x M5x25mm (or 20mm) hex bolt
4x M5 nut

For attaching assembly to a mic stand:
In the end you'll need 3/8 thread to screw everything onto a mic stand. I sacrifised the cheapest mic clamp I could get. (Stagg MH-8AH) This had a 5/8 thread bushing inside which I used to press fit into the Mic Stand Bracket. This allowed the use of a standard 5/8-3/8 thread adapter.

description.text:
I made this simple universal wall mounted holder for things.
Hope you like it.

Parts:

  • Thick cork mat (thickness: 6mm): https://www.castorama.pl/produkty/wykonczenie/tapety-i-wykonczenie-powierzchni/artykuly-korkowe/plyta-korkowa-6-mm.html
  • Thin cork place mat: http://www.ikea.com/gb/en/products/textiles-rugs/table-linen/avskild-place-mat-cork-art-40281654/
  • Large binder clips (Length: 2 inches, 51 mm): https://www.amazon.com/ACCO-Binder-Clips-Large-72100/dp/B002VD6BLG/
  • Glass on heatbed attached by small binder clip
  • 4x screw M3 30 mm

Tools:

  • Sharp knife
  • Driller-driver
  • Drill bits: 3 mm, 7 mm, 9 mm
  • The ruler and pen

Process:

  1. Print 4 parts (2x part "no hole", 1x "hole left", 1x "hole right", this hole is for wires).
  2. Use driller-driver and 3 mm bit to improve horizontal holes.
  3. Screw it using M3 screws (30 mm length).
  4. Cut two 24,8 mm squares in 6mm cork mat.
  5. Cut two 24,8 mm squares in 2mm cork mat.
  6. In one thin cork mat cut holes for small clip binders (green in the picture) and wires below the table (see the picture).
  7. Put 3 layers of cork mat into printed parts. At the bottom put thick cork mat and then two thin ones.
  8. Use driller-driver and 9 mm bits to make holes (in cork) for 4x bed springs.
  9. Use driller-driver and 7 mm bits to make hole (in cork) for bed wires.
  10. In second thick cork mat cut 22 mm square (in the middle) for heat bed.
  11. Place heat bed with attached glass (don’t forget to remove hooks?? from binder clips).
  12. Put second thick cork (with big hole), which should fill gaps between hotbed and printed parts.
  13. You can also cut another 25,4 mm cork square in thick mat. When you printer is warming, cover hot bed. In this way heat bed will reach proper temperature faster :-)

Remarks:

  • Maybe you also need holes in second thin cork mat, but holes only for small clip binders.
  • In OpenSCAD there is value latchOffset. I don't know whether this value is proper. I printed without this offset and I had to use sand paper to bigger space.
  • I don't know whether variable "wireHoleDiameter" is proper. I also printed without it. I had to use driller-driver to make hole for wires.

title: REEF BALL FOUNDATION Plaque for wall

description.text:
This thing was made with Tinkercad.

I used the image generator with the Reef Ball Foundation's logo inverted to negative and cleaned up to select colors. This can be printed in plastic and painted with logo colors then sealed with polyurethane or you can print in bronze or copper fill then put in a chlorine bleach bath for two days then seal in the patina with polyurethane. For underwater use on Reef Ball designed artificial reefs you must print in bronze and don't seal. You can use tinkercad to add a female metric screw thread to the back and use bronze or brass screws for mounting underwater..do not use dissimilar metals from what you print with or you will get corrosion. This plaque is suitable for use in Public Aquariums and displays when you have aquired free display Reef Balls from the Reef Ball Foundation. You should scale on your slicing software to the size you want but for most public displays and today's typical desktop 3-d printers go to your maximum print size.

** 8/16/2017 - Updated design at https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2482344***

I was having a problem with filament softening in the extruder housing and bending, creating jams. Kodama chose to piggyback the parts cooling fan onto the extruder cooling fan, which resulted in insufficient air flow through the extruder. This shroud positions a fan to draw air through the extruder housing and out the side exhaust. Its still a work in progress, as the shroud requires a piece of velcro on the top of the extruder housing and under the hook to stay in place. Creating a bow in the hook and extending the sides around the extruder housing will fix that, but I won't have time for a while, hence the velcro.

In using the shroud while printing a model that takes up the entire bed, I found that the wires from the extruder need to be routed over the output end of the fan using wire ties, as shown in the new picture above. As I'm using a low velocity fan, it doesn't impede the airflow significantly. If the wires are routed on the axis side of the shroud, they can catch on the end of the axis. If routed on the outside of the shroud, they overstretch the wire connections. I've also used wire ties to minimize the pulling of the connectors at the PCB end. I'm going to include wire management clips on the next version to avoid this issue.

title: EZ 18650 Charging Trays with Printed Spring
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
[Update: I had several request for 3-bay, so uploaded the odd 3-11 bay so all 1-12 are now included. Enjoy !]

I love enif's printable spring design battery holders, but found them too tedious to assemble quickly, somewhat flimsy in PETG due to the wire channels, and took a long time to print due to all the asthetics and fully enclosed nature, so I optimized an 18650 version of them for easy battery install/removal, faster and easier wire installation, and to print far faster with less material with some simple changes:

  • Removed all wire channels which allowed making the base 3 full print layers (@0.350mm) thinner (as such, all wiring must be routed externally)
  • Removed the double slots for battery terminals, allowing the wire to simply fold over the top for much easier wire install, and allow for easy soldering of the spring side if desired (which was nearly impossible with the original design)
  • Extended cylindrical bump designed to protrude wire for battery terminal to front-back of wall to allow one to wrap the wire around the top and twist around itself more easily
  • Reduced overall height to just under mid-level but still tall enough to catch a button-top cell (giving up ability to stack - mine can be used only single-layer)
  • Redesigned spring to remove double-width unsprung area (reducing width of each slot by 4 EWs)
  • Removed side and bottom cell recess grooves
  • Reduced walls between adjacent batteries to 2 shells (@0.45 EW)
  • Removed non-functional text and battery markings (since I configure these with spring side as + or -, depending on configuration)
  • Reduced wall height using a modified version of enif's "grip" recess feature

To use these, get either desoldering braid, tinned braid, or manually strip some 18 or 16 AWG wire and thread through the slots, folding over the top and twisting around itself. You can take a long strand and thread each hole, wrap once or twice, then continue to next hole, allowing parallel configuration as well.

I've printed 2 myself: one x8 that is configured 8S1P with each slot individual which I use with a set of 8S balance leads with aligator clips soldered on so I can quickly configure charging between x1 and 8x 18650 cells with my iCharger 308Duo. I also printed a x12 one and configured to 4S3P for use with an $8 Hobbyking LiPo charger and 4S balance lead with aligator clips to quickly charge up to 12 (or more if you have cells already tabbed together - see picture :) which is handy for charging up bulk 18650s that you may have reclaimed from laptop batteries.

The OpenSCAD file isn't ready for prime time as I just hacked it up to get the results I wanted, but is included for you determined souls (no Customizer on this one as I'm sure it would just croak on changing many of the parameters).

Results ?
The x12 unit printed in just 1hr-35min and the 8x printed in just 1hr-5min using stock "Fast 0.35" setting on my Prusa Research i3 MK2.

Enjoy !

title: micro adjustable 18mm round sensor probe mount

description.text:
I switched my inductive sensor from the stock SN04 for a more sensitive sensor. Most mounts for the round sensors have them left and front of the print head which by default has it off the bed when it tries to complete the autohome function. I remixed a couple of other designs to come up with this one.

You'll need 4 - 4MMx8 bolts to attach the adapter for the X axis bearing block. Snap off the wings, they are there to ensure the adapter doesn't warp. May need to clean up the edges. Before mounting the adapter, insert two M3 nuts in the lower set of hex shaped holes to allow the adjustable base to bolt up to the adapter.

In the sensor bracket, insert another m3 nut for the adjuster bolt (M3x45). You may need to lightly file/sand the back of the bracket to allow it to move smoothly in the base. Not to much, you don't want a sloppy fit. I used a M8x20 spring to provide the expansion force between the sensor bracket and the mounting bracket.

title: Universal telescope eyepiece smartphone mount V2

description.text:
Problems at the original design:

  1. Cannot fix on short eyepieces (ex.10mm)
  2. The clip are pressing side phone's buttons
  3. Eyepiece rubber ring must be removed to use the holder
  4. Cannot use the holder on other eyepiece's than standard 1'25(ex. planetary 5mm)

Fixes:

1.Narrowed the part in contact with the eyepiece (17mm)
2.Redesigned the clips to not touch side phone's buttons
3.Clearance for the rubber ring on the eyepiece's holder part, so no longer need to remove it.
4.Redesigned the holder part at eyepiece, so you can fix it on bigger eyepieces but also can hold on standard 1'25 eyepieces.
Thanks for the author of the original design!
